<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-09-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-09-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="24" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d24">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.00/841.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-09-07">
                                    <hi rend="italic">September 7, 1911</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>In Szechwan the situation is worse. British Consul General at Chengtu
                            recommends his Legation to advise all British subjects to leave that
                            city, but the Minister is disinclined to do so, believing such action
                            might increase danger. Szechwan troops are suspected of sympathy with
                            malcontents.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Williams.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>